Importing ASAP-seq data for analysis in Seurat/Signac

Oliver Knight

Compiled: June 07, 2023

Introduction

Having finished processing our raw data, we are left with several outputs:

  1. Sequenced DNA fragments which flank Tn5 insertion sites, as well as their corresponding single cell barcode (from cellranger count)
  2. A count matrix of antibody capture and sample hashtags by single cell barcodes (from asap-to-kite)
  3. A list of single barcodes and to which donor genotype they belong to (from cellsnp-lite and vireo-snp)
  4. A list of barcodes which are estimated to be doublets based on the frequency of fragment overlap (from AMULET)
  5. Count matrices for each nucleotide of mitochondrial DNA, by single cell barcodes, as well as other information (from mgatk).

Now, we are going to create our object which we can perform downstream analyses on. Roughly, this consists of 5 steps:

  1. Importing raw peak data and creating a Seurat object with a Signac chromatin assay
  2. Removing low quality cells and doublets called by genotyping, fragment overlap and hashtags
  3. Calling fine peaks using a more specific peak-caller (MACS2)
  4. Counting paired insertions at each peak
  5. Adding mitochondrial genotyping data

Read in peaks and filter for main chromosomes

First, we read in cellranger-called peaks. We will replace these later with those called by MACS2, but because we want to make sure that we are only calling from high-quality cells there, we use this to perform initial object creation and low-quality-cell removal.

peaks <- c()
peaks$NK_CMVpos_exp3_libA <- read.table("../data/S3816_outs/NK_CMVpos_exp3_libA/outs/peaks.bed",
    col.names = c("chr", "start", "end")) %>%
    makeGRangesFromDataFrame()
peaks$NK_CMVpos_exp3_libB <- read.table("../data/S3816_outs/NK_CMVpos_exp3_libB/outs/peaks.bed",
    col.names = c("chr", "start", "end")) %>%
    makeGRangesFromDataFrame()
peaks$cellranger <- Reduce(union, peaks)
peaks$cellranger <- keepSeqlevels(peaks$cellranger, standardChromosomes(annotations)[1:24],
    pruning.mode = "coarse")

Read in called cells, ATAC fragment files, and generate peak-by-cell matrix

We then import then names of cellranger-called cells, and the fragment files. The fragment files are independent of peaks called and are simply the flanking regions of DNA where Tn5 inserted it’s transposon sequence. Finally we create the count matrix.

Removing low quality cells

Our first low quality cell removal comes from lists we generated in the command line using vireo and AMULET. These contain heterotypic genotype doublets, and heterotypic/homotypic fragment overlap doublets. Steps included in importing these files include ensuring the order of cells in both the Seurat object and metadata lists are in the same order, so that when we add genotype information into the metadata slot they correspond to the correct cells. We then set the main identifier of the seurat object to the genotype of each cell.

genotype_ids <- read.delim("../data/S3816_outs/NK_CMVpos_exp3_libA/genotype/donor_ids.tsv",
    header = T)

    ]

    ]

Calculate QC metrics of each cell

Next, we calculate two quality control metrics from the fragment files:

  1. The nucleosome signal, which is a visual assessment of the periodicity of reads aligned to the genome. The presence of clear nucleosome banding indicates successful fragmentation and transposition, reflecting the enrichment of accessible chromatin regions.
  2. The TSS enrichment score, which measures the enrichment of ATAC-seq reads around transcriptional start sites. Accessible chromatin regions near TSSs are expected to have a higher density of reads compared to other genomic regions.
for (i in 1:length(alldata.atac)) {
    print(paste0("Performing QC of ", names(alldata.atac[i])))
    DefaultAssay(alldata.atac[[i]]) <- "ATAC"
    Annotation(alldata.atac[[i]]) <- annotations
    alldata.atac[[i]] <- NucleosomeSignal(alldata.atac[[i]], verbose = F)
    alldata.atac[[i]] <- TSSEnrichment(alldata.atac[[i]], fast = FALSE, process_n = 10000,
        verbose = F)
}

## [1] "Performing QC of NK_CMVpos_exp3_libB"

Perform temporary clustering for MACS2 peak calling

We now perform a temporary dimensionality reduction in order to cluster our cells. We do this as we will perform peak-calling with MACS2, which is more fine with calling peaks. As different celltypes have different regions of openly accessibly chromatin, we need clustering information to be able to call peaks which may get lost by calling peaks at a bulk level. We perform this clustering on a temporary object, temp, and then overlay annotated clusters back onto our original objects.

for (i in 1:length(alldata.atac)) {
    print(paste0("Performing dimensionality reduction of ", names(alldata.atac[i])))
    temp <- alldata.atac[[i]]
    temp <- RunTFIDF(temp, verbose = F) %>%
        FindTopFeatures(verbose = F) %>%
        RunSVD(reduction.name = "lsi_atac") %>%
        FindNeighbors(reduction = "lsi_atac", dims = 2:11, k.param = 30, verbose = F) %>%
        FindClusters(graph.name = "ATAC_snn", resolution = 0.1, algorithm = 3, group.singletons = T,
            verbose = F)
    alldata.atac[[i]]$coarse_clusters <- temp$seurat_clusters
}

Count paired insertions

To understand why I like to use paired-insertion-counting (PIC), I would suggest reading this pre-print ‘Is single nucleus ATAC-seq accessibility a qualitative or quantitative measurement?’ This performs PIC and replaces the original matrix with one containing the MACS2-called peaks, and subsequently normalises our matrix for dimensionality reduction and beyond.

# create macs2 assay and remove original atac one
for (i in 1:length(alldata.atac)) {
    print(paste0("Counting paired insertions for ", names(alldata.atac[i])))
    counts <- PIC_counting(colnames(alldata.atac[[i]]), alldata.atac[[i]]@assays$ATAC@fragments[[1]]@path,
        peaks$macs2.total)
    alldata.atac[[i]][["ATAC"]] <- CreateChromatinAssay(counts = counts, sep = c(":",
        "-"), fragments = alldata.atac[[i]]@assays$ATAC@fragments[[1]]@path)
    Annotation(alldata.atac[[i]]) <- annotations
    alldata.atac[[i]] <- RunTFIDF(alldata.atac[[i]])
}
